# /etc/sudoers.d/cogno-deploy — the ONLY root privilege the CI deploy user has.
#
# Install (root:root, 0440 — sudo ignores a file that is group/world-writable, and refuses to run at all
# if it cannot parse one, so validate BEFORE you move it into place):
#
#     visudo -c -f deploy/sudoers.d/cogno-deploy          # parse-check the repo copy first
#     sudo install -m 0440 -o root -g root deploy/sudoers.d/cogno-deploy /etc/sudoers.d/cogno-deploy
#
# The filename must contain NO DOT and no `~`: sudo's #includedir skips those, silently, and you would
# spend an afternoon wondering why NOPASSWD is not taking effect.
#
# Why this is safe to hand a CI system:
#
#   • It grants exactly one command. Not `systemctl`, not `install`, not a shell — one root-owned
#     script (deploy/scripts/cogno-deploy-node) whose behaviour is fixed and version-controlled. The
#     deploy user cannot edit it: /usr/local/sbin is root-owned.
#
#   • The trailing "" pins it to ZERO ARGUMENTS. This is the part that is easy to get wrong. A bare
#     `NOPASSWD: /path/to/script` permits that script to be run with ANY arguments — and since the
#     script installs the file it is pointed at, as root, into a world-readable 0755 path, an argument
#     would be a read-any-file-on-the-box primitive. `""` means "this command, with no arguments".
#
# So a stolen deploy key buys an attacker exactly what a stolen deploy key should buy: the ability to
# ship a node binary and bounce the relay. Not root on the droplet.
#
# The user below is the DEPLOY_USER from the workflow's secrets (the droplet's `cogno`, which is both
# the SSH deploy user and the relay's service user). Change both if yours differs.

cogno ALL=(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/local/sbin/cogno-deploy-node ""
